public static void main(String[] args) {
	Display display = new Display();
	Shell shell = new Shell(display);
	shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());
	final Text text = new Text(shell, SWT.BORDER | SWT.MULTI);
	text.addKeyListener(new KeyAdapter() {
		public void keyPressed(KeyEvent event) {
			String mask = "";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.CTRL) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.CTRL ";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.SHIFT) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.SHIFT ";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.ALT) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.ALT ";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.COMMAND) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.COMMAND ";
				
			System.out.println
(mask+" "+event.character+" "+event.keyCode);
                        System.out.println(Integer.toHexString
(event.character));

		}
	});
	shell.setSize(200, 200);
	shell.open();
	while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
		if (!display.readAndDispatch()) {
			display.sleep();
		}
	}
}

Bug.WithStack:
KeyListener understand the SHIFT as stateMask but not the CTRL and the ALT 
(c.f. the example below)


        this.channelText.addKeyListener(new KeyListener()
        {

            public void keyPressed(KeyEvent event)
            {


                //  This works
                if ((event.stateMask == SWT.SHIFT) && (event.character == 'c' 
|| event.character == 'C'))
                {
                    //                    channelText.append("SHIFT+C");
                    channelText.copy();
                }
                //  This doesn't work
                if ((event.stateMask == SWT.CTRL) && (event.character == 'c' || 
event.character == 'C'))
                {
                    //                    channelText.append("CTRL+C");
                    channelText.copy();
                }
            }

            public void keyReleased(KeyEvent e)
            {
                // TODO Auto-generated method stub

            }

        });
For the Ctrl + C case, the event is coming in but the character is not "C" 
or "c" but the ascii value 3 which maps to "^C".

For the ALT + C case, the Alt key down comes in but not the second event.

Assigning to Steve to give additional info for this user.

Here is a simple test case:

public static void main(String[] args) {
	Display display = new Display();
	Shell shell = new Shell(display);
	shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());
	final Text text = new Text(shell, SWT.BORDER | SWT.MULTI);
	text.addKeyListener(new KeyAdapter() {
		public void keyPressed(KeyEvent event) {
			String mask = "";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.CTRL) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.CTRL ";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.SHIFT) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.SHIFT ";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.ALT) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.ALT ";
			if ((event.stateMask & SWT.COMMAND) != 0) mask 
+= "SWT.COMMAND ";
				
			System.out.println
(mask+" "+event.character+" "+event.keyCode);
                        System.out.println(Integer.toHexString
(event.character));

		}
	});
	shell.setSize(200, 200);
	shell.open();
	while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
		if (!display.readAndDispatch()) {
			display.sleep();
		}
	}
}
The character field represents the final character value after all modifier 
keys have been applied.  For example, the character is 'A' when Shift+'a' is 
typed.  When Ctrl+'a' is typed, the character is ^A (ASCII 0x01 sometimes 
called SOH).  In the case of Alt, this modifier does not affect the character 
value.
Please address the ALT key problem.

The ALT key problem only occurs if there is no menubar in the application.
Appending a related message from eclipse.tools, for reference (and, perhaps a
workaround?! - my product release will use R2.1!):

From: adrian <stori@ca.ibm.com>
Newsgroups: eclipse.tools
Subject: [SWT] R2.1: Only KeyUp event for Alt+[Shift]+<char> on Windows
Date: Mon, 31 Mar 2003 11:26:42 -0500
Organization: EclipseCorner

In R2.1 Alt+<char> and Alt+Shift+<char> key combinations do *not* 
generate a KeyDown event on Windows, unlike all the other keys.  That 
means that I have to put listeners on both KeyDown and KeyUp in order to 
capture all the keys.

That would be fine, but it makes it very difficult to ignore the KeyUp 
events which correspond to the preceding KeyDowns that I have already 
processed (the down & the up events are not always 100% identical in 
their keyCode, character, and stateMask - e.g., press Shift, press A, 
release Shift, release A).  Is there any easy way out of this??
Fixed > 20030331
Note that this only happens when there is no menu bar in a shell.  If you are 
seeing another case, please reopen this PR with a snippet that shows the 
problem.  Thanks.
Hmmm, my problem is with an editor view inside Eclipse - which certainly does
have a menu bar!?  In any case, I'll try a later build too, which should have
your fix.
Your key is being eaten by an Eclipse accelerator.  Try a simple stand alone 
example with a menu bar to prove that this is true.
I'll try soon with the fixed driver.  Please note, however, that it's not one
