public boolean isPersistent(MarkerInfo info) {
	if (!cache.isPersistent(info.getType()))
		return false;
	Boolean isTransient = (Boolean) info.getAttribute(IMarker.TRANSIENT); 
	return isTransient == null || !isTransient.booleanValue();
}

public boolean isPersistent(MarkerInfo info) {
	if (!cache.isPersistent(info.getType()))
		return false;
	Object isTransient = info.getAttribute(IMarker.TRANSIENT); 
	return isTransient == null || !(isTransient instanceof Boolean) || !
((Boolean)isTransient).booleanValue();
}

Bug.WithStack:
2.1 RC2

The new "transient" marker attribute (see bug 9267) has a boolean type. A 
marker is now persistent if its type is persistent and its transient attribute 
is not set to true.

The code in MarkerManager for checking if a given marker is persistent will 
fail (throws a ClassCastException) in a lot of different contexts if for some 
reason the user has set the attribute to a non-boolean value:

public boolean isPersistent(MarkerInfo info) {
	if (!cache.isPersistent(info.getType()))
		return false;
	Boolean isTransient = (Boolean) info.getAttribute(IMarker.TRANSIENT); 
	return isTransient == null || !isTransient.booleanValue();
}

It should use "instanceof Boolean" before casting:

public boolean isPersistent(MarkerInfo info) {
	if (!cache.isPersistent(info.getType()))
		return false;
	Object isTransient = info.getAttribute(IMarker.TRANSIENT); 
	return isTransient == null || !(isTransient instanceof Boolean) || !
((Boolean)isTransient).booleanValue();
}

Since the attributes have simple names, we may be breaking clients that are 
already using a "transient" attribute in their own plug-ins. And since 
persistence checking is done in a lot of places (setting any attribute, 
removing markers, saving markers, etc), it may be hard to understand the reason 
of the failure.
Fixed and released to HEAD.

